This is likely due to changes made to geode in [GEODE-10126](https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/GEODE-10126), where these Geode properties were removed. In Geode these properties were [marked experimental in Geode 1.14](https://geode.apache.org/releases/latest/javadoc/org/apache/geode/distributed/ConfigurationProperties.html#REDIS_ENABLED), so removing them was not considered a breaking change. Spring Data Geode should remove references to these properties for the next release that is intended to work with Geode 1.15.

* Add a 'org.eclipse' Logger configuration.
* Add a 'org.eclipse.jetty' Logger configuration.
* Add a 'org.springframework.geode.cache.service' Logger configuration.
* Add a 'org.springframework.geode.config' Logger configuration.", 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/spring-projects/spring-boot-data-geode/commits/5addaa4eca7f5dfc8c84e81546841312c1b68089'}, {'sha': '19799d10c8332da58ed7a25994486766e121e445', 'author': {'email': 'jblum@vmware.com', 'name': 'John Blum'}, 'message': 'Disable overridden and custom dependency management for Eclipse Jetty.

Apache Geode 1.14.4 is based on Eclipse Jetty 9; However, Spring Boot 3 upgraded the declared and managed Eclipse Jetty dependency to 11 in order to align with the Jakarta EE 9 migration and baseline.

Rolling back the Eclipse Jetty version override and dependency management to again align with Spring Boot 3.

Resolves #116.', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/spring-projects/spring-boot-data-geode/commits/19799d10c8332da58ed7a25994486766e121e445'}, {'sha': 'd368cc892971ed19dc60e764b3858123aa8293ee', 'author': {'email': 'jblum@vmware.com', 'name': 'John Blum'}, 'message': 'Add apache-geode-jetty11 module to integrate Apache Geode 1.14 with Eclipse Jetty 11.

Apache Geode 1.14 is based on Eclipse Jetty 9.  Spring Boot 3 declares and manages Eclipse Jetty 11 to align with the Jakarta EE 9 specification as a baseline.

Resolves #116.', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/spring-projects/spring-boot-data-geode/commits/d368cc892971ed19dc60e764b3858123aa8293ee'}, {'sha': '0f2933de070f4158fa667f1c63a04dd982e6ae29', 'author': {'email': 'jblum@vmware.com', 'name': 'John Blum'}, 'message': 'Declare the apache-geode-jetty11 as a test runtime dependency in the spring-geode-autoconfigure module.

Replaces the old Apache Geode geode-http-service test runtime dependency, which was based on Eclipse Jetty 9, which causes a conflict with Spring Boot 3 declaring and managing Eclipse Jetty 11 in order to align with the Jakarta EE 9 specification as a baseline.

Closes #116.', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/spring-projects/spring-boot-data-geode/commits/0f2933de070f4158fa667f1c63a04dd982e6ae29'}]}

'body': "Currently, when Apache Geode `1.14.x` is upgraded to **Eclipse Jetty 11** (in order to match _Spring Boot_ `3.0` and the Jakarta EE 9 specification), then the following log messages is output in the Apache Geode peer `Cache` node's log:

```txt
2022-04-13 21:07:20,782  WARN geode.internal.cache.InternalHttpService:  86 - 
Could not enable HttpService: 'void org.eclipse.jetty.server.SslConnectionFactory.<init>(org.eclipse.jetty.util.ssl.SslContextFactory, java.lang.String)'
```

This log messages is output when Apache Geode's embedded HTTP service (`HttpService`), which is based on **Eclipse Jetty**, is initialized on startup.

Upon closer analysis (debugging), the underlying root cause of the problem is:

```java
java.lang.NoSuchMethodError: 'void org.eclipse.jetty.server.SslConnectionFactory.<init>(org.eclipse.jetty.util.ssl.SslContextFactory, java.lang.String)'
    at org.apache.geode.internal.cache.InternalHttpService.createJettyServer(InternalHttpService.java:131
    at  org.apache.geode.internal.cache.InternalHttpService.init(InternalHttpService.java:81)
    at org.apache.geode.internal.cache.GemFireCacheImpl.initializeServices(GemFireCacheImpl.java:1505)
    at org.apache.geode.internal.cache.GemFireCacheImpl.initialize(GemFireCacheImpl.java:1432)
    at org.apache.geode.internal.cache.InternalCacheBuilder.create(InternalCacheBuilder.java:191)
    at org.apache.geode.internal.cache.InternalCacheBuilder.create(InternalCacheBuilder.java:158)
    at org.apache.geode.cache.CacheFactory.create(CacheFactory.java:142)
    at org.springframework.data.gemfire.CacheFactoryBean.createCache(CacheFactoryBean.java:227)
...
    at org.springframework.context.support.AbstractApplicationContext.refresh(AbstractApplicationContext.java:583)
    at org.springframework.boot.SpringApplication.refresh(SpringApplication.java:730)

'comments': 0, 'created_at': '2022-04-12T20:15:51Z', 'updated_at': '2022-04-12T20:15:51Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'MEMBER', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'Many Exception messages contain exclamation marks (!) at the end of the Exception message, for example:

> "_Object must not be null!_"

While this alerts the user to an immediate problem in his/her code, it could be construed as abrasive.

Additionally, using any form of punctuation in Exception messages is not conducive for chaining.  Generally, in Java Exception/Error (Throwable) chaining, the messages from the underlying Exceptions (causes) are chained together with the outer, wrapping Exception, for example:

```java
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException: "Message from the wrapping IllegalArgumentException followed by; Message of the caused by Exception"
  at ...
caused by: java.lang.IllegalStateException: Message of the caused by Exception
  at ...
```

That is, the Exception messages from the chain are appended and separated by the `;`. 

If the messages from the wrapping Exceptions in the Exception chain contain punctuation, then it can lead to confusing text:

```java
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException: "Object must not be null!; Message of the caused by Exception"
  at...
caused by: java.lang.IllegalStateException: Message of the caused by Exception
  at ...
```

{'push_id': 9608959574, 'size': 1, 'distinct_size': 1, 'ref': 'refs/heads/2.6.x', 'head': '480f9ccffa52b7ad5d9f7caaee98337128f42af9', 'before': '3d2df962a8ae222632143ef96d71653356ff74cb', 'commits': [{'sha': '480f9ccffa52b7ad5d9f7caaee98337128f42af9', 'author': {'email': 'odrotbohm@vmware.com', 'name': 'Oliver Drotbohm'}, 'message': "Fix PersistentEntity lookup in AbstractMappingContext.hasPersistentEntity(…)

Looking up a PersistentEntity via ….getPersistentEntity(…) applies some massaging of the given type as it could be a proxy type created for a user type. That wrangling was not applied in ….hasPersistentEntity(…) which resulted in a call to that method with a proxy type yielding false although it shouldn't if we already have a PersistentEntity available for the corresponding user type.

We now explicitly lookup the entity by original type and, if it's not the user type itself, try to look up the entity for the latter.

Fixes #2589.", 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/jxblum/spring-data-commons/commits/480f9ccffa52b7ad5d9f7caaee98337128f42af9'}]}

Closes #2576', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/jxblum/spring-data-commons/commits/e25fb0b16a5874a65754a52f6c0fcd36eac2296c'}, {'sha': '1792cd8f452cac9376d80e72892c8a6fcd6574ec', 'author': {'email': 'odrotbohm@vmware.com', 'name': 'Oliver Drotbohm'}, 'message': "Fix PersistentEntity lookup in AbstractMappingContext.hasPersistentEntity(…)

Looking up a PersistentEntity via ….getPersistentEntity(…) applies some massaging of the given type as it could be a proxy type created for a user type. That wrangling was not applied in ….hasPersistentEntity(…) which resulted in a call to that method with a proxy type yielding false although it shouldn't if we already have a PersistentEntity available for the corresponding user type.

We now explicitly lookup the entity by original type and, if it's not the user type itself, try to look up the entity for the latter.
